dmunds, Suffolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Mobberley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Mobberley (Cheshire)."],"variants":[{"name":"Mobberly","meanings":["English:  see  Mobberley  ."]},{"name":"Moverley","meanings":["English: a Yorks variant of   Mobberley  ."]},{"name":"Moberly","meanings":["English (southern): habitational name from Mobberley in Cheshire. The placename derives from Old English <i>mōt</i> ‘meeting’ + <i>burg</i> ‘fortress’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’."]},{"name":"Moberley","meanings":["English (Worcestershire and Hampshire): variant of   Moberly  ."]},{"name":"Mobley","meanings":["English: shortened form of   Moberly  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William de Mobberley I was born in 1335, in Mobberley, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom as the son of William Mobberley. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Mrs. William De Mobberly. He died in 1426, in his hometown, at the age of 91."},"et":{"1335–1426":"1335–1426","1330–Female":"1330–Surnud","1360–Male":"1360–Surnud","1377–1494":"1377–1494","1300–Male":"1300–Surnud","1426":"1426","1335":"1335","1377":"1377","1300":"1300","1330":"1330","1494":"1494","1360":"1360","Mobberley, Cheshire, England":"Mobberley, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bury St Edmunds, Suffolk, England":"Bury St Edmunds, Suffolk, England"},"fi":{"1335–1426":"1335–1426","1330–Female":"1330–Kuollut","1360–Male":"1360–Kuollut","1377–1494":"1377–1494","1300–Male":"1300–Kuollut","1426":"1426","1335":"1335","1377":"1377","1300":"1300","1330":"1330","1494":"1494","1360":"1360","Mobberley, Cheshire, England":"Mobberley, Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Bury St Edmunds, Suffolk, England":"Bury St Edmunds, Suffolk, England"},"fr":{"1335–1426":"1335–1426","1330–Female":"1330–Décédée","1360–Male":"1360–Décédé","1377–1494":"1377–1494","1300–Male":"1300–Décédé","1426":"1426","1335":"1335","1377":"1377","1300":"1300","1330":"1330","1494":"1494","1360":"1360","Mobberley, Cheshire, England":"Mobberley, Cheshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Bury St Edmunds, Suffolk, England":"Bury St Edmunds, Suffolk, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"William de Mobberley I est né en 1335, à Mobberley, Cheshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, fils de William Mobberley. Il a eu au moins 1 fils et 1 fille avec Mrs. William De Mobberly. Il est décédé en 1426, dans sa ville natale, à l’âge de 91 ans."},"de":{"1335–1426":"1335–1426","1330–Female":"1330–Ve